 over coordinate paths, and idley suggests that a wavelet basis might be
 better than a fourier basis.
 But is this the case? Maybe not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The primary successs of the Fourier basis is due to Newton's 2nd Law in
 flat space.
 In a vacuum, in a non-interacting environment, in flat space, a moving
 mass moves at constant momentum.
 The momentum distribution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\left(p-p_{0}\right)$
\end_inset

 and the corresponding wave is a plane wave 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{ikx}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the philosophical reason why plane waves provide the prefered basis
 for QFT in Minkowski space.
 There's also a second reason: conservation of energy.
 The kinetic term 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(d\varphi/dt\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is translation-invariant.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 a plane-wave, the kinetic terms is trivially 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a wavelet in flat space, it's a bit silly.
 So, in a wavelet basis
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi\left(t\right)=\sum_{n,0\le m\le2^{n}}a_{n,m}f\left(2^{n}t-m\right)
\]

\end_inset

for a mother wavelet 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, the kinetic term just becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\sum_{n}2^{n}\sum_{0\le m\le2^{n}}a_{n,m}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

with the second sum illustrating the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

silliness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the wavelet basis: the wavelet basis was not translation-invariant (by
 construction), but the kinetic term is translation-invariant, and so the
 second sum is just a sum over all translated versions of the wavelet.
 In flat space, this is quite pointless and silly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, we arrive at an impass.
 We're interested in writing down an orthonormal basis in curved space.
 The fourier transform is problematic: the need to integrate over the entire
 real line, the implicit conservation of momentum implied by plane waves.
 These two properties make it ideal for flat space, but problematic for
 curved space with either coordinate singularities or real singularities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavelet basis is hardly any better.
 The wavelets are localized, but even then, there's a built-in assumption
 of flatness at the local scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the correct, best basis for arbitrary paths in curved spacetime?
 I don't know.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Proper time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When one writes down some arbitrary path through spacetime, there arises
 the problem of assigning a numeric value to the integral of the kinetic
 term 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{T}dt\left(d\varphi/dt\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 for that path.
 What is the correct metric for the time, along that curve? There are several
 possibilities(!!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The issue is that any diffeomorphic rescaling of the time coordinate along
 the curve gives the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

same curve
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in coordinates, but assigns a different energy to it.
 Thus, the sum over paths cannot be just a sum over spatially distinct paths,
 but also a sum over diffeomorphic rescalings of the time coordinate.
\end_layout

