\begin_layout Section*
Appendix 1.C: Toy String Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Toy example for strings.
 Except its not strings, because spacetime is taken to be 1D instead of
 2D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But first, lets provide the background motivation.
 The traditional, conventional Einstein-Hilbert action in 4D is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\frac{1}{16\pi}\int d^{4}x\sqrt{g}\left(R+\Lambda\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 the Ricci scalar and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 the cosmological constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum gravity partition function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Z=\int\left[dg\right]\exp\left(-L\right)
\]

\end_inset

The measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[dg\right]$
\end_inset

 is supposed to be over all spacetimes, up to diffeomorphism.
 That is, average over all spacetime geometries.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above is exactly solvable for 1-D spacetime, i.e.
 for 1-D quantum gravity.
 Toy example due to Ed Witten; cribbed from some youtube lecture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two possible spacetimes: closed loop, open curve.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Metric tensor 
\begin_inset Formula $g=g_{tt}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times1$
\end_inset

 metric tensor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There's no Riemann curvature tensor, so the Ricci scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $R=0$
\end_inset

.
 So it gets boring, unless we introduce matter fields.
 Do this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Action is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=\int dt\sqrt{g}\left(\frac{g_{tt}}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(\frac{dX_{i}}{dt}\right)^{2}-\frac{m^{2}}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for scalar fields 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\cdots,N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda=m^{2}/2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canonical momentum:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{i}=\dot{X_{i}}=\frac{dX_{i}}{dt}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1-D 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Einstein field eqn
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is obtained by taking the variation of the action w.r.t.
 the metric tensor, i.e.
 by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta L/\delta g=0$
\end_inset

.
 This gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}P_{i}^{2}+m^{2}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantize to get wave function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-\sum_{i}\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial X_{i}^{2}}+m^{2}\right)\psi\left(X\right)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is interpreted as an exactly solvable theory of quantum gravity in
 one dimension, which describes a spin-0 particle of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 propagating in 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

-dimensional spacetime.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Minor generalizations include using a non-Euclidean metric 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{ij}$
\end_inset

 for the scalar fields, plus adding gauge fields, so that the wave eqn is
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-G_{ij}\frac{D}{DX_{i}}\frac{D}{DX_{j}}+m^{2}\right)\psi\left(X\right)=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Partition function requires integrating over all metrics on the 1-D manifold,
 modulo diffeomorphisms.
 However, the 1-D manifold has only one invariant (up to diffeomorphism)
 and that is the total length 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

, which is taken as the elapsed proper time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Do this in two steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First step is from Feynmann & Hibbs (1965) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Quantum Mechanics and Path Integrals
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (must-read book.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Write down the QM Feynman path integral for the Hamiltonian is 
\begin_inset Formula $H=P^{2}+m^{2}$
\end_inset

, using the shorthand 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{2}=G_{ij}P^{i}P^{j}$
\end_inset

.
 This is going to be the Fourier x-form of the matrix elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-\tau H\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This gives the QM propagator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\left(x,y;\tau\right)=\int\frac{d^{N}p}{\left(2\pi\right)^{N}}e^{ip\cdot\left(x-y\right)}\exp\left(-\tau\left(p^{2}+m^{2}\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

The above is interpreted as the Feynmann path integral, an integral over
 all possible paths 
\begin_inset Formula $X\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 that start at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 and end at 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=\tau$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, integrate over all possible metrics 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{tt}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

, up to diffeomorphisms.
 Since there is only one invariant, this integral is just an integral over
 all possible spacetimes 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G\left(x,y\right)=\int_{0}^{\infty}d\tau G\left(x,y;\tau\right)=\int\frac{d^{N}p}{\left(2\pi\right)^{N}}e^{ip\cdot\left(x-y\right)}\frac{1}{p^{2}+m^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x,y\right)=Z\left[J\right]$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 are the currents 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 that we need to differentiate by, to obtain interactions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So what does this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

actually say
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

? It says that the conventional relativistic Klein-Gordon eqn in 4 dimensions
 (or in N dimensions) is the same thing as quantum gravity in 1 dimension.
 We can then build up conventional QFT from here, by adding interaction
 terms to the Klein-Gordon eqn.
\end_layout

